text: hi everyone
Anthony Fantino here internet's busiest
music nerd and it's time for a review of
the new Nick Cave and the Bad Seeds
album push the sky away Nick Cave is an
Australian singer-songwriter and the
London band that he currently leads is
on its 15th studio LP laying another
collection of songs on top of the
group's ever-growing and impressively
consistent discography the songs that
Nick Cave and the Bad Seeds turn out
tend to be kind of dark tortured or
melancholy or have this element of
stomach-churning viciousness to them and
while there are other CD
singer-songwriters that I do enjoy quite
a bit like Tom Waits for example Nick
Cave has always kind of reached down
into that lower level just that next
level of seediness between songs like
Mickey Mouse and the goodbye man from
the new Grindr man LP the birthday
party's album's tracks like where the
wild roses grow up jump the devil good
son I constantly find myself asking when
I listen to much of what is related to
Nick Cave is Nick Cave deeply disturbed
I know Nick Cave has had his more pg-13
moments over the years but I really do
feel like that there are either parts of
his brain that he has been cursed with
all his life or maybe we all have those
parts in our brains and most of us are
just kind of afraid to explore them or
think about them obviously Nick Cave is
not dangerously insane because he's
managed to hold together a music career
that really any musician would be proud
of plus he's covered an impressive group
of genres over the years post-punk goth
rock alternative rock baroque pop as
well as Foulke Nick Cave and his band
maybe went a little easier on the ears
in the 2000s the darkness was still
there they weren't as brash as they were
with their earlier noisier post-punk
stuff it was I guess in a sense tortured
but a bit more mature
however in
years Nick Cape has been kind of getting
back to his punk rock punk blues and
garage rock roots not only with new Bad
Seeds releases like dig Lazarus dig and
abattoir blues but the recent formation
of his band grinder man and even though
it's really only been a couple years
since we've heard from Nick Cave through
grinder man it has been a while since
we've heard from the Bad Seeds I mean
really since about 2008 with dig Lazarus
dig which is more than enough time for
some kind of stylistic or emotional
reinvention and before this LP even came
out there was this sense for me anyway
that this LP would be receding back to
Nick caves more sort of melancholy side
especially because of the cover which
looks like some kind of awkward breakup
going on in a French new-wave film and
the few tracks that drop before this LP
Jubilee Street which does have an
intense ending but is nowhere near Nick
caves most intense song and we know who
you are which is really one of the more
somber tracks I've heard Nick Cave put
out in recent years so of course when I
sat down to listen to the entire LP it
was no surprise that push the sky away
overall is a much moodier experience
than most of Nick caves output almost as
if it were conceived in this sort of
depressive state fueled by a very sad
personal experience and some of what
happens on this LP does seem to kind of
shake cave in a personal way which is
something that for a Bad Seeds fan is
somewhat of a rare treat because often
Nick Cave is sort of playing this
narrator character or a character within
a story that he's penning for a song
that he's singing you're not really
getting a moment like off this LP
finishing Jubilee Street where he kind
of sings specifically about finishing
the track and how the imagery the dream
inspired imagery off of that song has
this deep emotional significance to him
that has him kind of distraught which
I'm sure for some Bad Seeds fans is
going to be extremely intriguing to kind
of see him in
in this emotional state for an entire
albums length but for me personally I
mean I really missed despite how many
times I listened to this album I really
missed the gusto the fire the looming
gloom and doom that cave typically
brings to a track with the exception of
the track Jubilee Street I really did
not get even a whiff of that character
that has told so many twisted stories
over the years and it's not really the
sadness or the melancholy about this
album that has me kind of you know
wandering other places with in my head
when I'm listening to this thing I mean
it really kind of feels like in a way
Nick Cave has shrunken into himself and
and it's difficult for him to project
the emotions that he is feeling with the
power that he typically does and and
while yeah this isn't the most musical
part of the album you know we're not
exactly getting down to instrumentation
here we're talking about vocal delivery
we're talking about personality but I
personally feel that Nick caves music is
nothing if not extremely personality
driven and if the personality isn't
there for me the magic isn't there and
this magic only shows up occasionally
mostly on the first half of the LP and
the LP here is not very long it's just
about 42 minutes but to me it feels much
longer despite only having nine tracks
and that's mostly because the
songwriting on this LP isn't all that
sharp or concise it's not all that
ballad driven or anything like that with
the exception of maybe a few songs the
songs on this LP aren't
compartmentalized or cutting like they
are on albums like the Bauman's call or
Henry's dream instead Nick Cave uses a
songwriting a performing technique that
he's been using on and off over the
years very consistently on the grinder
man LPS and recent output from the Bad
Seeds where he basically grabs a groove
he grabs a musical idea and it sort of
gets you know jammed out repeated in a
sense over and over and over as he kind
of tells his tale and sings over it it's
more of a linear way of songwriting it's
a more linear way of song performing and
this
Niq is executed awesomely on Jubilee
Street where the track just gets more
and more intense as it goes along you
get this sense that you're moving from
point A to point B as the song finishes
not only because Kate is telling this
story with detailed lyrics but the
instrumentation gets hotter it gets
heavier strings sort of seep in however
there are moments on this LP where I
personally feel like cave really needed
to I guess sort of edit himself and
maybe you know bring some of these songs
down boil them down into a sharper
ballad like we get on the song we know
who you are
like on the song wide lovely eyes which
just to me feels like this very tame
almost adult contemporary piece of
gospel inspired songwriting and a lot of
the instrumentation on this track
especially the guitar riff feels just
robotically and kind of annoyingly
looped behind everything sort of taking
away the the flow and the intimacy out
of this song and in others on here too
like we real cool this is an issue that
I had off a dig Lazarus dig too a lot of
the instrumentation felt chopped it fell
looped but I feel like what kind of made
that album scrape by anyways is the fact
that so many of the songs were just loud
and in-your-face and energetic in my
opinion it's not working so well here on
these softer and slower tracks and the
songs that don't really have any clear
loops in them and kind of wander around
a little bit more when it comes to
what's being said and the
instrumentation for example the song
mermaid the atmosphere is really nice
the instrumentation on this track swells
really awesomely but in my opinion the
story that Nick tells and the vocals he
sings them with on this track are really
unengaging and just don't do anything
for me emotionally whatsoever it just
doesn't come in and grab me or lure me
in either again this is a point where
Nick Cave seems kind of shrunken inside
of himself and not really projecting
much of anything other than some mumbles
some kind of indulgences that don't
really have any significance to me maybe
to him overall to me the song was
unmemorable
kind of uneventful and borderline
unbearable and when the song finishing
Jubilee Street comes on it becomes very
apparent to me that Nick Cave is not
personally insane at all possibly
because we're getting this very personal
look at his feelings and I mean they
actually come off pretty mundane with
how he's delivering them how they're
being performed in the sense through his
vocals and his storytelling the group
vocals and the keyboards on the hook are
really nice but Nick caves lyrics and
his storytelling they wander and meander
more than the whittling banjo all over
this track in terms of a tale and in
terms of songwriting it's really a
musical bridge to nowhere just kind of
fading out into the the nothing that it
conjured the closing track on here the
title track is extremely lackluster as
well with even more unengaging vocals
from Nick Cave against these watery
boring synthesizers that just don't do
anything for me from beginning to end
there was just not really much about
this album that I found to be
spectacular I wouldn't hold it up to
anything from Nick Cave and the Bad
Seeds early stuff I wouldn't even hold
it up to anything from their most recent
two LPS
while I'm still going to look forward to
the next Bad Seeds LP this album just
did not move me whatsoever I mean sure
it didn't offend me or really have any
terrible awful horrible songs on it but
I mean when you pile all of these tracks
on top of one another it just becomes
this long very beige kind of experience
that doesn't really you know do much
emotionally lyrically musically it just
kind of repeats repeats repeats mumbles
I mean to me that's that's what pushed
the sky I mean adds adds up to its again
it's just my opinion but I'm feeling a
strong four to a light five on this LP
if you've given it a listen
what did you think of it did you love it
